:: Changing minds and organising for open access {"position":"1300,1300","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Changing Minds and Organising for Open Access </h1>
How you organise for open should reflect your organisation’s capacity, goals and needs. Identifying these early on will help your organisation shape a tailored strategy suited to everyone’s needs. 

A move to open might be motivated by many goals:

<ul><li>Aligning policies with copyright law and funding obligations on open access</li>
<li>Improving staff efficiency by redirecting time to mission-critical work </li>
<li>Improving collections visibility and engagement</li>
<li>Increased good will and positive attention from local, national and international publics</li>
<li>Serving stakeholders, from national funders to locals, such as residents, tourists, schools, historical societies, creators and business</li>
<li>Delivering on commitments to equity, diversity and inclusion</li>
<li>Exploring the new business models and programming enabled by open </li>
<li>Serving the organisation by diversifying income streams to be more sustainable and resilient </li>
<li>Joining the growing open GLAM movement</li></ul>
Open access implementation is at its best when everyone feels involved. Getting everyone on board may be easy or hard depending on your organisation’s structure. 

With Art UK, this means [placeholder - explain process in concrete terms - is this a matter of approval? Something else].
