:: Commercialisation and open innovation {"position":"850,1300","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Commercialisation and Open Innovation</h1> Going open with Art UK does not prevent you from using those images to generate income. Your approach to open should be tailored to your organisation’s needs. 

To model those needs, consider that few organisations maintain sufficient data year-on-year to track image licensing income and demonstrate what, if any, is profit versus income. Moreover, exclusive control of images is not necessary to generate revenue through them. Evidence from organisations with open collections shows that overall income is not necessarily reduced. Staff have been redirected to support open access and other mission-critical work. 

Open organisations maintain or diversify revenue through:

<ul><li>Print-on-demand and other merchandising</li>
<li>Commercial partnerships</li>
<li>Licensing of specialty services and consultancy during use of open collections</li>
<li>New research collaborations and funding driven by the open policy</li>
<li>Service fees for high-resolution images and new photography</li>
<li>Increased visibility leading to new opportunities, foot traffic, and other indirect revenue</li></ul> Organisations also report that financial concerns did not materialise as initially feared or imagined. Experiences have shown:

<ul><li>A decline in image licensing income for years</li>
<li>Image licensing services did not produce profits after accounting for overheads</li>
<li>Loss of image income was primarily attributable to researchers and educators who needed specific artworks for teaching, articles and career advancement</li>
<li>Staff retention is essential for the transition from image licensing to new open programming and innovation activities</li>
<li>Other revenue streams remain stable or improve, including commercial partnerships and grant income</li>
<li>Traditional impact and revenue metrics do not measure indirect income and other value added through open </li></ul> You can learn more about Art UK open access and commercialisation case studies in [[open access with Art UK]] and [[Open access on display]]
<h2>I want to learn more about:</h2>
<span class="btn-link-outline"> <a href="https://www.glamelab.org/products/making-the-business-case-for-open-access/">How to make the business case for open access at my organisation .</a></span>

