:: Copyright clearance and risk {"position":"425,1300","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Copyright Clearance and Risk</h1>
Assessing the copyright status of artworks may involve some ambiguity or risk. 
A balanced, phased approach can help your organisation develop a clearance process that maximises the positive impacts of open access while mitigating other risks or concerns.

Art UK provides copyright and risk assessment services to all collections prior to publishing images on the platform. This involves:

<ul><li>Following a structured copyright assessment process to identify public domain materials, with support from Art UK</li>
<li>Using standard tools to clearly label both public domain and in-copyright works on the platform</li>
<li>Maintaining a robust take down policy</li>
<li>Clearly clearly communicating the limits and possibilities of public reuse through our Copyright, Open Access, and other webpages</li></ul> More than a decade of international evidence suggests that many anticipated risks are often lower than expected, while benefits can be significant. Open access is based on established legal principles, particularly for public domain works that do not raise liability issues. 

By contrast, legal and reputational risk can follow when copyright is asserted in public domain reproductions, given the growing legal and sector consensus internationally that these images do not receive a new copyright protection.

