:: Creative Commons licences and tools {"position":"725,1300","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Creative Commons Licences and Tools</h1>
Creative Commons (CC) is the nonprofit organization behind the well known set of public licenses and tools for openly sharing creative and public domain content. 
The two tools available for <strong>public domain content</strong> include CC0 1.0 Universal Public Domain Dedication and Public Domain Mark 1.0. 

<a href="https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/">CC0</a> is a legal tool used to dedicate materials to the public domain which communicates to users worldwide
<img src=https://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/buttons/88x31/svg/cc-zero.svg  width="90">

PDM is a legal tool used to identify materials that are free of all known restrictions under copyright law, including related and neighbouring rights. 
<img src=https://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/buttons/88x31/svg/publicdomain.svg  width="90">

While either tool is appropriate, Creative Commons recommends using CC0 for digital reproductions of public domain works. This is because:

<ul><li>Digital assets often contain multiple content types, from the depiction of the underlying work to the digital image itself, as well as any image metadata.</li>
<li>CC0 is the most legally-interoperable statement for cross-border users, reassuring these users that the materials can be reused for any purpose, regardless of copyrights or related rights that may be recognised in the country of use.</li>
<li>Users are more likely to credit the organisation and artist when using materials released as CC0.</li></ul> In most cases, you will not have any copyright to waive. Nonetheless, Creative Commons recommends applying CC0 to ensure that copyright laws in other countries will not prevent the use of that object, reproduction or metadata for users within those countries. 

The two open licenses available for <strong>copyright content</strong> include CC BY Attribution 4.0 International and CC BY-SA Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International.
<a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">CC BY 4.0</a> (Attribution) allows reuse for any purpose so long as credit is given to the creator. 
<img src=https://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/buttons/88x31/svg/by.svg width="90">

<a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/">CC BY-SA 4.0</a> (Attribution-ShareAlike) allows reuse for any purpose so long as credit is given to the creator and the materials are shared under the same open terms. 
<img src=https://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/buttons/88x31/svg/by-sa.svg width="90">

Even if rights arise, you can choose to dedicate the works to the public domain. For this, use the CC0 1.0 Universal Public Domain Dedication. 
<h2>I want to learn more about:</h2>
<span class="btn-link-outline"> <a href="https://www.glamelab.org/products/copyright-clearance-handbook-for-public-domain-publications/">The nitty-gritty of clearing rights and assigning CC0 to images and data produced by my organisation.</a></span>

<span class="btn-link-outline"> <a href="https://www.glamelab.org/products/selecting-an-alternative-license-or-label/">The broader range of licenses, labels and tools available for communicating rights and use restrictions around heritage materials.</a></span>

