:: Misuse and loss of control {"position":"1150,1300","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Misuse and loss of control </h1>
Many organisations express concerns that images may be misused, misattributed, or used inappropriately, or that commercial use will benefit others, rather than the organisation who produced the images. 

Free commercial use of the public domain is exactly what the expiration of copyright is designed to allow. Many commercial uses bring greater visibility to the organisation, the artists and their works.

When policies are designed around misuse and loss of control, they can shut down a wide range of educational, creative, and non-commercial engagement with collections.  

The Art UK platform supports responsible public use with:
<ul><li>Clear image reuse statements to indicate what is permissible</li>
<li>Credit lines to improve attribution practices </li>
<li>Guidance on the importance of attribution and responsible use of the public domain</li></ul> <h2>Frequently asked questions on misuse and loss of control</h2><h3>Can I use CC BY or CC BY-SA to ensure users credit my organisation? </h3>
No. Open licences like CC BY and CC BY-SA cannot be applied to reproductions of public domain artworks. While your organisation may want users to attribute the organisation as the source, this valid request does not justify the application of a copyright license where no copyright arises. 

Instead, use a public domain tool and educate users about good citation practices. 

Europeana’s <a href ="https://www.europeana.eu/en/rights/public-domain-usage-guidelines">Public Domain Usage Guidelines</a> encourage users to give credit where credit is due and show respect for the original work and creator, along with other good practice tips on use of public domain materials. 

Creative Commons recommends <a href = "https://creativecommons.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Nudging-Users-to-Reference-Institutions-when-Using-Public-Domain-Materials%E2%80%94Creative-Commons-Guidelines-1.pdf">a simple framework</a> to support behavioural change and encourage positive outcomes by nudging users to reference organisations when using public domain materials.  <h3>How have open organisations responded to misuse and loss of control?</h3> Placeholder - [Need to discuss how ‘scary’ we want these examples to be. For example:
An CC0 image of a Chinese tapestry from the Metropolitan Museum of Art or Getty Institute (?) was used on the cover of a special issue by a medical journal focused on COVID-19.
CC0 images from the Metropolitan Museum of Art were used in PornHub’s Classic Nudes project, which they released a response to saying they are not in the business of policing how people use public domain materials.
We could respond with: 
- Merete Sanderhoff’s quote that loss of control is part of open, and that’s a good thing
- Karin Glasman’s quote that copyright assertions don’t prevent bad people from doing bad things, but does prevent people from doing good things
- Data from the Yellow Milkmaid Syndrome report about Rijksmuseum’s images becoming the go-to source for the painting after open access, rather than the thousands of poor-quality images that were already available on the internet, scanned from books, postcards, in black and white, etc.]
<h3>What about AI?</h3> Placeholder - [This one is inevitable, but the question is how hard we want to lean into the “its all inevitable” - or whether we want to refocus that attention on Art UK plans to provide commercial income streams for AI use, etc?]
