:: Understanding ‘open’ and what it means {"position":"300,1300","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Understanding open and what it means</h1>
<p>At its core, going ‘open’ means recognising that when an organisation digitises an object there is no new copyright in that newly-created file. This central principle should inform the localised open access strategy that is based on your organisation’s needs. 

Thousands of heritage organisations around the world have adopted open practices. Referred to as ‘open GLAM’ (Galleries, Libraries, Archives and Museums), this movement enables the world-at-large to reuse images of cultural heritage in the public domain for any purpose, without permission. 

Open GLAM overlaps with other open initiatives, like open access publishing, open culture, open science, open data, open source, and open innovation. This informal network of open movements helps one another build new systems, avoid problems, and share successes as they grow together. 

Going open does not have to be an all-or-nothing decision for an organisation. You can go open on Art UK while considering what open looks like for other collections in ways that can meet ongoing organisational needs.</p><h2>I want to learn more about:</h2><span class="btn-link-outline"> <a href="https://www.glamelab.org/products/go-open-with-glam-e/">Building an open access programme, including what that means in practice for the organisation, collections and wider community.</a></span>

<span class="btn-link-outline"> <a href="https://www.glamelab.org/products/internal-open-access-policies/">Identifying works in the collection that may be good candidates for developing an open access policy. </a></span>

<span class="btn-link-outline"> <a href="https://www.glamelab.org/products/open-licensing-a-digital-heritage-leadership-briefing/">A snapshot of open licensing practices and decision making across the UK heritage sector. </a></span>

